## Section 5 - What i performed

* Designed the **Fetcher** as a dedicated networking component responsible solely for downloading web pages from the internet.
* Selected **libcurl** as the HTTP client library and gained an understanding of its request lifecycle and callback-based mechanism for receiving response data.
* Designed the **FetchResult** structure to encapsulate the downloaded HTML, HTTP status code, and other request-related information.
* Explored a threshold-based approach for distinguishing between static HTML pages and JavaScript framework-based pages, but discarded the idea because a crawler starting from a seed URL has no reliable initial baseline for determining an appropriate threshold.
* Finalized a modular crawler architecture in which the **Fetcher** retrieves web content, the **Framework Detector** determines whether browser rendering is required, and the **Render Engine (CDP)** is invoked only for pages that require JavaScript execution.
* Added the URL Normalizer module to the project documentation and created a workflow diagram illustrating the complete URL normalization process, making the normalization pipeline easier to understand and maintain.

## Section 6 — Learning Reflection

This session helped me understand that URL normalization is much more than converting text to lowercase. Different URL representations can point to the same resource, so applying normalization rules before storing URLs is essential for preventing duplicate crawling. Separating each normalization rule into independent helper functions also improved the maintainability of the module.

This session improved my understanding of HTTP communication in C++. I learned that libcurl receives webpage data in multiple chunks through callback functions instead of returning the complete response at once. I also learned the importance of using the correct development environment. Installing **UCRT64** allowed me to use the latest libcurl packages and provided a stable environment for future crawler development.

